  "answer_summary": "Globotriaosylceramide (Gb3/GL-3) accumulates in Fabry disease because of deficient alpha-galactosidase A (α-Gal A) enzyme activity, encoded by the GLA gene on Xq22.1. α-Gal A normally cleaves terminal α-galactosyl residues from Gb3 in lysosomes. Mutations in GLA reduce or abolish this hydrolytic activity, causing Gb3 to progressively accumulate in lysosomes of vascular endothelial cells, renal podocytes, cardiomyocytes, and neurons, leading to multi-organ dysfunction. Gb3 is synthesized by A4GALT (Gb3 synthase), which adds α-1,4-galactose to lactosylceramide. The deacylated form, globotriaosylsphingosine (lyso-Gb3), also accumulates and serves as a key biomarker.",
